r son needs. He is gited and extremely bright in math, science, music and languages. Our public schools teach to the median level of understanding and he was board stiff. The time it woudl take to fight the system would be years of my son's life spent at a public school that might still never change even if I did expend inordinate amounts of time and energy trying to improve it. Our public schools do not work for the students who really want to learn and who are trying to keep up with the educational challenges presented in teh 21st century. There is a reason why our students in the US do not test well against their international peers, it is because they are not getting the support at home that they need and their schools are providing the most average quality product that they can because the schools are run for the benefit of the teachers and their unions, not for the benefit of the students. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1216" language="en" documentId="2702" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Leslie Andren" date="Aug 29, 2013 8:26PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="10" thumbsDown="0" origId="2702" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1216"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>